    <note>Han(1) Cuiyan [656] Guohua's [651] grandson, Qi(1)'s [630] son, Ju(1)'s [641] and Ju(2)'s [642] nephew, Chunyan's [7031] and Zhongyan's [644] brother, Zhengyan's [635] cousin. His sons-in-law were Cai(1) Zhuang [3855] (twice: sororate), Cai(1) Jian [3853], and Cai(1) Jing's [1649] son, Diao [3866]. The son's of Cuiyan used radical 75 in their generational name, whereas those of Zhongyan used radical 85 indicating lineage segmentation. Zhongyan and his son, Zhi [3320], were purged as members of the Yuanyou coalition. Perhaps the affinal alliance with the Cai(1) explains the absence of any indication that Cuiyan's [656] descendants held office during the Southern Song. He had fourteen sons. Zhao Dingchen, WJ, 17.1a-12b, 10a; XCB, 489.17a, 17a (n.); SHY:ZG, 67.35a. CBD, 5, 4178-9.</note>
